Introduction

This notebook is only for exploring transaction data

Daily transactions would be important to define an engagement metric

Found from an article that PayPal tracks below metrics to measure business performance:

  1. Conversion Rate (%of successful transactions)
  2. Total payment volume
  3. Total transactions
  4. Average transaction amount
  5. Unique Users
  6. Monthly active users
  7. New user creation rate
  8. Error rate
  9. Decline rate
  10. False positive rate (declined users who could have been good - based on test and control analysis)
  11. Loss rate

My aim would also be to check daily trends of these metrics (as many as possible) from provided transaction file.

Number of transactions are constantly increasing which is a good sign. There is also a sharp drop in Dec18 which is likely because most people stay at home during Christmas holiday periods and eventually spend less.

<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x24219750860>

COMPLETED transactions and ALL transactions have exactly similar trends which suggests it is most common transaction type (obviously)

Trend of rate 

<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x242192a6630>

It's clear that FAILED and REVERTED transactions were pretty high in first quarter of 2018, draggin COMPLETED transactions down. Eventually over the course of the time, all transactions have stabilized which is a good sign for the business.

DECLINED transactions have been very stable throughout, good to see that upsurge of customers have not caused havoc in the system.

There is a sudden increase in PENDING transactions after Mar19, this needs to be investigated further.

Analysis on AMOUNT

Trend of All Amounts 

<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x24217b5ac88>

There are some unusually high transactions. Profile report shows that 95% of amount_usd values are below 200.

Creating a new column with capped amount and also a flag to keep track of users attempting unusual transactions.

Assumption-2 : Large transaction amounts are sign of potential frauds

Trend of Capped Amounts 

<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x24217b26cf8>

Trend across Trasaction States 

<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x2421707e2e8>

DECLINED transactions were high in initial periods and have relatively stablized at the end. CANCELLED transactions are the most fluctuating followed by FAILED transactions. REVERTED and PENDING transactions are of relatively low size.

In all this mess, COMPLETED transactions have completely suppressed and have absolutely no visibility. Since COMPLETED transactions would be the one generating true customer experience for the product, it makes sense to only keep focus on COMPLETED transactions and drop all other transaction states to remove noise from data.

Assumption-3 : Only COMPLETED transactions are going to develop true customer engagement

Trend of Only Completed Transactions 

<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x242165f0198>

There are still many high ticket transactions every month which are skewing the distribution big time.

Let's check distribution of log-transformed value of amount column.

<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x24219753d30>

It's clear that distribution of amount column acorss months is pretty stable, and even outliers are pretty much same each month.

Few high ticket transactions each month is good for business, though I am slight concerned about no steady increase in median value over months (expected since the volume is steadily increasing). This infers that all new customers have very similar spending/usage behaviour.

Assumption-4: All customer (new & old) have similar spending behaviour since there is no increase in median value of amount across months

Clustering 

<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x24237930d68>
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x24237984da0>

 [-0.2336551   3.40665254]

  • Cluster 0 : these users have overall avgerage amount of spending within an average time duration which makes them engaged
  • Cluster 1 : these users have relatively high average of spending amount with a mix of both low and high duration
  • Cluster 2 : these users have low average of spending amount but their spend duration is also low which makes them enaged on the platform
  • Cluster 3 : these users have long duration b/w their transactions which is definitely a sign of disengagement

Clustering distribution is not as clean as expected, though it can be seen that cluster 0 & 2 users are more engaged with the product and cluster 3 is not (long gaps between their transactions)

Clusters 1 center can be used as a boundry to define engaged customers

Summary

During this analysis following inferences and assumptions have been developed to set a definition for engaged user

Assumption-1: Data is not correct after April19 and safe to ignore.
Assumption-2: Large transaction amounts are sign of potential frauds.
Assumption-3: Only COMPLETED transactions are going to develop true customer engagement.
Assumption-4: All customer (new & old) have similar spending behaviour since there is no increase in median value of amount across months.
Assumption-5: REFUND, CARD_REFUND, FEE, TAX & CASHBACK transaction types are not useful for defining an engagement of a user.

Overall, constant increase in number of transactions and users is happy sign for the business whereas there are also few setbacks in terms of sharp drop in new customer acquisition rate and insignificant change in median value of spend amount in over 16 months.

**New user acquisition rate = (No. of users doing their first trasaction in a particular day)/(No. of users in that day)

This has been constantly declining and by the end of April19 has reached to its minimum value, which is particulary a worry sign for business.

**AvgDuration = (No. of days between first and last transaction)/Total No. of transactions

Note that this was calculated only for COMPLETED transactions.

AvgAmount of COMPLETED Transactions along with AvgDuration helped in seggregating engaged customers from unengaged one.

Conclusion

K-Means clustering approach between transformed dimensions of average amount of transaction and average duration between successive transactions for users has been taken to define engaged customers (cluster center is used to set thresholds)
